05487nam a22007455i 9780823250141DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232501417 a10.1515/97808232501412doi  a(DE-B1597)555266  a(OCoLC)1019665805  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aD805.I55bS78 2010 7aHIS0271002bisacsh04a940.53171 aStutterheim, John K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Diary of Prisoner 17326 :bA Boy's Life in a Japanese Labor Camp /cJohn K. Stutterheim. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (228 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWorld War II: The Global, Human, and Ethical Dimension00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. A Teenaged Prisoner of Japan, No. 17326 -- tChapter 2. Discovering Java -- tChapter 3. Malang -- tChapter 4. Merbaboe Park -- tChapter 5. War -- tChapter 6. Uncertain Times in Malang -- tChapter 7. Kesilir -- tChapter 8. The Final Days of De Wijk -- tChapter 9. The Transport -- tChapter 10. Lampersari -- tChapter 11. The Benteng -- tChapter 12. Camp Bangkong -- tChapter 13. Horseplay -- tChapter 14. The Diary -- tChapter 15. The Disease of Despair -- tChapter 16. Bleak Prospects -- tChapter 17. Death and Unexpected Freedom -- tChapter 18. Hidden Dangers -- tChapter 19. The British -- tChapter 20. Escape from Hell -- tChapter 21. A Family Again -- tChapter 22. Time to Fly -- tChapter 23. Surabaja Restored -- tChapter 24. To Holland on Oranje -- tEpilogue -- tGlossary 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this moving memoir a young man comes of age in an age of violence, brutality, and war. Recounting his experiences during the Japanese occupation of the Dutch East Indies, this account brings to life the shocking day-to-day conditions in a Japanese labor camp and provides an intimate look at the collapse of Dutch colonial rule.As a boy growing up on the island of Java, John Stutterheim spent hours exploring his exotic surroundings, taking walks with his younger brother and dachshund along winding jungle roads. His father, a government accountant, would grumble at the pro-German newspaper and from time to time entertain the family with his singing. It was a fairly typical life for a colonial family in the Dutch East Indies, and a peaceful and happy childhood for young John. But at the age of 14 it would all be irrevocably shattered by the Japanese invasion.With the surrender of Java in 1942, John's father was taken prisoner. For over three years the family would not know if he was alive or dead. Soon thereafter, John, his younger brother, and his mother were imprisoned. A year later he and his brother were moved to a forced labor camp for boys, where they toiled under the fierce sun while disease and starvation slowly took their toll, all the while suspecting they would soon be killed.Throughout all of these travails, John kept a secret diary hidden in his handmade mattress, and his memories now offer a unique perspective on an often overlooked episode of World War II. What emerges is a compelling story of a young man caught up in the machinations of a global war-struggling to survive in the face of horrible brutality, struggling to care for his disease-wracked brother, and struggling to put his family back together. It is a story that must not be forgotten.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBoyszIndonesiazJavavDiaries. 0aDutchzIndonesiazJavavDiaries. 0aPrisoners of warzIndonesiazJavavDiaries. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, Dutch. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, Indonesian. 0aWorld War, 1939-19